      "modified": "2026-04-13T19:44:29.000Z",
      "name": "Critical Remote Code Execution Vulnerability in Fortinet FortiOS Actively Exploited (CVE-2025-1234)",
      "description": "CISA has added CVE-2025-1234 to its Known Exploited Vulnerabilities (KEV) catalogue after confirming active exploitation in the wild. The vulnerability is a critical heap-based buffer overflow in Fortinet FortiOS, present in versions 7.0 through 7.4, affecting FortiGate firewalls and SSL-VPN appliances. Successful exploitation allows an unauthenticated remote attacker to execute arbitrary code with root privileges. Multiple threat actors are believed to be exploiting this vulnerability to gain initial access to enterprise networks, with subsequent deployment of ransomware and data theft tooling observed in several cases. Organisations running affected versions are urged to apply Fortinet's emergency patch immediately. Network defenders should review FortiGate logs for evidence of exploitation and consider taking affected appliances offline if patching cannot be completed urgently.",
